Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers trick individuals into revealing sensitive
information such as passwords, bank details, or OTPs by pretending to be a trustworthy source.
This is commonly done through fake emails, messages, or websites that appear legitimate.
A typical phishing attack happens in several steps. First, the attacker creates a fake message that
looks like it is from a trusted organization, such as a bank or online service. Next, the victim
receives this message, often containing urgency like “Your account will be blocked.” The
message includes a malicious link that redirects the user to a fake website designed to look real.
When the victim enters their login credentials or financial details, the attacker captures this
information. Finally, the attacker uses the stolen data to access accounts or commit fraud.
Phishing attacks usually target students, working professionals, and elderly individuals who may
not be fully aware of online threats. People who frequently use online banking or shopping
platforms are especially vulnerable.
The consequences include financial loss, identity theft, and unauthorized account access. Victims
may also face stress and reduced trust in digital systems
